1
00:00:13,567 --> 00:00:15,000
<i>Your mom didn't seem like
herself</i>

2
00:00:15,133 --> 00:00:16,000
<i> when she woke up earlier.</i>

3
00:00:16,133 --> 00:00:17,200
<i> She looked really out of it.</i>

4
00:00:17,333 --> 00:00:18,700
<i> Sir Manuel, are you crying?</i>

5
00:00:18,833 --> 00:00:24,433
<i>I'm just happy I was here
when Felma woke up.</i>

6
00:00:24,567 --> 00:00:26,033
<i> Dear your dad. Your real dad.</i>

7
00:00:27,567 --> 00:00:29,867
<i> I think I saw him last night.</i>

8
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,700
<i> Jojo, is that really you?</i>

9
00:00:31,833 --> 00:00:34,367
<i>Actually, I'm supposed to be
at the airport right now.</i>

10
00:00:34,533 --> 00:00:36,733
<i>But you said in your message
that it was urgent.</i>

11
00:00:36,867 --> 00:00:38,000
<i> So...</i>

12
00:00:38,133 --> 00:00:39,133
<i> did something happen?</i>

13
00:00:39,267 --> 00:00:41,667
<i>Felma was looking for you
when she woke up.</i>

14
00:00:41,800 --> 00:00:44,500
<i> Manuel is here, too, Felma.</i>

15
00:00:47,667 --> 00:00:50,933
<i>- What are you doing here?
- Felma! Felma!</i>

16
00:00:51,067 --> 00:00:51,900
<i>Dad, why did you come home
so soon?</i>

17
00:00:52,033 --> 00:00:53,000
<i> Did you leave Mom there?</i>

18
00:00:53,133 --> 00:00:57,033
<i>The truth is, your mom's memory
was affected.</i>

19
00:00:57,167 --> 00:00:58,533
<i>She doesn't want to see me
anymore.</i>

20
00:00:58,667 --> 00:01:00,900
<i> Dad, please don't lose hope.</i>

21
00:01:01,033 --> 00:01:03,367
<i>We love you so much.
Don't ever forget that.</i>

22
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:06,000
<i>Come here.
Let me hug my loved ones.</i>

23
00:01:14,700 --> 00:01:24,667
Noah, I don't remember
the wedding.

24
00:01:27,100 --> 00:01:29,533
But...

25
00:01:30,167 --> 00:01:36,067
I remember the proposal.

26
00:01:36,767 --> 00:01:41,567
I was happy back then.

27
00:01:42,633 --> 00:01:47,233
You accepted me as I am.

28
00:01:48,433 --> 00:01:56,000
And the kids, too.

29
00:01:56,133 --> 00:02:06,100
You wanted to marry.

30
00:02:08,600 --> 00:02:12,133
Because I love
the people you love.

31
00:02:12,267 --> 00:02:19,633
When will the kids visit?

32
00:02:19,800 --> 00:02:21,700
I'll call them.

33
00:02:21,833 --> 00:02:25,633
Is there anything you want them
to bring here?

34
00:02:27,733 --> 00:02:37,700
I want to see and hug them.

35
00:02:46,533 --> 00:02:47,867
<i> Dad,</i>

36
00:02:48,367 --> 00:02:52,767
what if it takes a long time
before Mom's memories come back?

37
00:02:52,900 --> 00:02:56,400
What if she keeps being sweet
to Uncle Noah?

38
00:02:59,067 --> 00:03:02,967
Dear, that's the reality we have
to face right now.

39
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:05,267
But like you said, right?

40
00:03:06,367 --> 00:03:09,100
It's just because of the surgery
and her illness.

41
00:03:09,233 --> 00:03:10,967
That's why I truly believe...

42
00:03:12,167 --> 00:03:14,967
I believe the day will come
when she remembers

43
00:03:15,100 --> 00:03:16,700
that she already forgave me.

44
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,867
And I'll patiently wait
for that day to arrive.

45
00:03:30,800 --> 00:03:40,767
Noah, thank you for being there
as a father to the kids

46
00:03:55,100 --> 00:04:05,067
after their useless dad
abandoned us.

47
00:04:15,333 --> 00:04:18,967
Thank you.

48
00:04:26,067 --> 00:04:36,033
I want to go home now
so I can cook for you, kids.

49
00:04:38,333 --> 00:04:42,833
Oh my, Mom, we really love that,
too.

50
00:04:45,300 --> 00:04:47,633
Mom, your cooking is still
the best.

51
00:04:48,700 --> 00:04:58,667
Your favorite afritada?

52
00:05:04,567 --> 00:05:10,433
Mom, I'm the one who loves
your afritada the most.

53
00:05:10,567 --> 00:05:14,100
The one with fried potatoes,
right?

54
00:05:16,067 --> 00:05:21,667
And for me, Mom,
I like Dad's laing.

55
00:05:24,567 --> 00:05:27,200
Whose cooking?

56
00:05:28,467 --> 00:05:34,867
I don't want to hear that name!

57
00:05:35,033 --> 00:05:45,000
I don't want to hear that name!

58
00:05:45,200 --> 00:05:47,933
Felma, please calm down.
Calm down, calm down!

59
00:05:48,067 --> 00:05:49,067
- Mom, Mom, Mom...
- It's nothing, nothing...

60
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:50,667
Don't get mad at the kids.

61
00:05:52,100 --> 00:05:54,700
Calm down, calm down.

62
00:05:54,833 --> 00:05:56,033
Relax.

63
00:05:59,667 --> 00:06:04,300
Sorry, kids.

64
00:06:05,400 --> 00:06:15,367
I don't want to hear anything
about that man.

65
00:06:23,067 --> 00:06:25,433
Mom, please get well soon, okay?

66
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:32,800
Everyone at FMP is already
waiting for you.

67
00:06:32,933 --> 00:06:36,333
FMP?

68
00:06:38,267 --> 00:06:48,233
When is Sisig ni Bunso's launch?

69
00:06:51,400 --> 00:06:52,400
Mom,

70
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:56,667
Sisig ni Bunso was launched
a while ago.

71
00:06:57,867 --> 00:07:01,500
It's one of our bestsellers now.

72
00:07:11,300 --> 00:07:19,333
Why is this happening to me?

73
00:07:19,500 --> 00:07:28,433
I don't remember.

74
00:07:28,567 --> 00:07:36,100
What if I don't remember
anything at all?

75
00:07:36,233 --> 00:07:39,933
I'm scared.

76
00:07:40,067 --> 00:07:46,667
I'm scared.

77
00:08:03,100 --> 00:08:04,033
Ta-da!

78
00:08:04,167 --> 00:08:05,800
Surprise!

79
00:08:05,933 --> 00:08:07,467
Hi, sis.

80
00:08:07,600 --> 00:08:09,267
Do you remember me?

81
00:08:09,400 --> 00:08:11,533
Sis.

82
00:08:13,767 --> 00:08:17,233
Father Pio, thank you.
She remembers me.

83
00:08:17,367 --> 00:08:19,433
Sis.

84
00:08:19,567 --> 00:08:21,867
Sis...

85
00:08:22,033 --> 00:08:24,067
so pretty.

86
00:08:25,600 --> 00:08:27,400
Oh, sis.

87
00:08:27,533 --> 00:08:31,667
Of course, you'd remember me.
My beauty is unforgettable.

88
00:08:31,800 --> 00:08:32,733
Yes!

89
00:08:32,867 --> 00:08:34,133
That's why we're friends, sis.

90
00:08:34,267 --> 00:08:36,900
We're both beautiful.

91
00:08:37,033 --> 00:08:42,233
Are we both beautiful?

92
00:08:42,367 --> 00:08:45,800
You're funny.

93
00:08:47,333 --> 00:08:49,900
Very funny.

94
00:08:50,033 --> 00:08:50,833
Okay.

95
00:08:50,967 --> 00:08:52,233
Thanks, sis.

96
00:08:52,367 --> 00:08:54,467
It's the same
as calling me a clown.

97
00:08:54,633 --> 00:08:56,900
You're driving me nuts.

98
00:08:57,033 --> 00:09:00,067
You really know
how to ruin the moment.

99
00:09:00,900 --> 00:09:03,500
You could've just gone
along with what I was saying

100
00:09:03,633 --> 00:09:05,267
before throwing me
under the bus.

101
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:08,100
I'm offended, okay?

102
00:09:15,167 --> 00:09:18,067
You know, sis,
I need to admit something.

103
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:19,467
I was slightly...

104
00:09:20,767 --> 00:09:23,500
I was kind of nervous
on my way here.

105
00:09:23,633 --> 00:09:27,067
I was actually scared.
I thought...

106
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:28,933
you might forget me.

107
00:09:30,533 --> 00:09:32,333
Sis, I wouldn't survive that.

108
00:09:33,733 --> 00:09:38,133
What if I came here
and you didn't know I was Paz?

109
00:09:38,267 --> 00:09:40,767
That I was your best friend?

110
00:09:40,900 --> 00:09:43,300
What if you suddenly
pushed me away?

111
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:46,567
What about everything
we've been through together?

112
00:09:47,433 --> 00:09:50,367
Ever since we were kids,
you've been my best friend.

113
00:09:52,633 --> 00:09:54,867
What will happen to
all our memories?

114
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:57,000
Honestly, sis,

115
00:09:57,767 --> 00:10:04,067
I'm even closer to you and your
kids than to my own blood.

116
00:10:04,233 --> 00:10:05,633
Because of your illness,
it's like...

117
00:10:06,567 --> 00:10:09,167
it control, alt, delete Paz.

118
00:10:10,967 --> 00:10:14,733
Sis, that would destroy me.

119
00:10:14,867 --> 00:10:17,000
My God, I can't
handle that.

120
00:10:18,300 --> 00:10:20,433
I really can't.

121
00:10:26,667 --> 00:10:33,767
I will never forget you.

122
00:10:33,900 --> 00:10:43,867
I love you so much.

123
00:10:54,167 --> 00:10:56,633
Sis...

124
00:10:56,767 --> 00:10:58,933
I love you so, so much, too.

125
00:11:00,833 --> 00:11:02,667
I love you very much.

126
00:11:21,667 --> 00:11:23,500
Is that true?

127
00:11:23,633 --> 00:11:24,900
Yes, friend.

128
00:11:25,033 --> 00:11:28,500
Tess, my nurse gossip buddy,
sounds reliable.

129
00:11:28,633 --> 00:11:33,500
She said she was there
when Felma pushed Manuel away.

130
00:11:33,633 --> 00:11:36,200
With matching hurtful words.

131
00:11:36,333 --> 00:11:40,167
Even while she was stuttering.

132
00:11:40,300 --> 00:11:42,333
Poor Manuel.

133
00:11:44,933 --> 00:11:47,200
Serves him right!

134
00:11:47,333 --> 00:11:50,400
Now he knows what rejection
feels like.

135
00:11:50,533 --> 00:11:52,200
Manuel totally
deserves that.

136
00:11:52,333 --> 00:11:53,433
Karma.

137
00:11:53,567 --> 00:11:57,000
And after that explosive scene,

138
00:11:57,133 --> 00:11:59,700
he wasn't allowed
back into the room.

139
00:11:59,833 --> 00:12:03,800
He could only look at Felma
through the crack in the door.

140
00:12:06,633 --> 00:12:08,233
So...

141
00:12:08,933 --> 00:12:10,767
he's loving her from afar now?

142
00:12:10,900 --> 00:12:13,100
That kind of vibe?

143
00:12:14,233 --> 00:12:16,233
You know what
I've been thinking, Alice?

144
00:12:16,400 --> 00:12:21,067
What if I reapply
at Southcrest Hospital?

145
00:12:21,200 --> 00:12:24,033
I'll just mess
with Flirty Felma and Manuel.

146
00:12:24,167 --> 00:12:25,233
Friend, wait.

147
00:12:25,367 --> 00:12:28,867
Remember, you're already
banned from the hospital?

148
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:31,600
Don't worry.
I still have an ace.

149
00:12:31,733 --> 00:12:35,100
I've got leverage against Manuel
and his illegitimate family.

150
00:12:35,233 --> 00:12:37,833
You really think you never
run out of aces, huh?

151
00:12:37,967 --> 00:12:40,200
Well, that's just
your imagination.

152
00:12:40,333 --> 00:12:43,500
Most of the time,
your big moves backfire.

153
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:49,233
Sorry.

154
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:52,100
Just keeping it real.
Don't get mad, friend. Don't be.

155
00:12:53,867 --> 00:12:58,867
You're saying that because you
don't know the latest story yet.

156
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:01,533
Just wait and see, friend.

157
00:13:01,667 --> 00:13:03,533
You'll find out soon enough.

158
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:11,100
Miss Felma...

159
00:13:11,767 --> 00:13:13,733
your recovery process...

160
00:13:14,367 --> 00:13:16,300
is really a team effort.

161
00:13:17,367 --> 00:13:20,200
We'll need help
from other therapists.

162
00:13:20,767 --> 00:13:24,133
Immediately,
a physical therapist,

163
00:13:24,700 --> 00:13:26,567
an occupational therapist,

164
00:13:27,167 --> 00:13:30,933
and a speech-language
pathologist or speech therapist.

165
00:13:32,300 --> 00:13:36,933
So, Doctor, you mean
she'll be able to talk, walk,

166
00:13:37,067 --> 00:13:40,767
move, think,
and function normally again?

167
00:13:41,400 --> 00:13:44,100
Yes, with consistent therapy
and proper rest.

168
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:46,600
The frontal lobe can...

169
00:13:47,800 --> 00:13:50,533
reorganize and recover.

170
00:13:51,300 --> 00:13:53,900
And with your therapists...

171
00:13:56,867 --> 00:14:01,400
we'll guide you through
the process.

172
00:14:01,800 --> 00:14:02,567
Sir.

173
00:14:03,633 --> 00:14:04,567
Good morning.

174
00:14:06,100 --> 00:14:08,733
Miss Felma,
I'd like you to meet

175
00:14:09,567 --> 00:14:12,400
your physical therapist,
Joselito Cañares.

176
00:14:12,533 --> 00:14:14,233
Good morning, Miss Felma.

177
00:14:14,800 --> 00:14:17,467
He'll help
strengthen your muscles

178
00:14:17,600 --> 00:14:22,200
and improve your balance
so you can walk again.

179
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:29,167
I like your vibes.

180
00:14:29,633 --> 00:14:31,733
You're good-looking.

181
00:14:32,700 --> 00:14:37,667
You look like a celebrity.

182
00:14:46,233 --> 00:14:47,333
Hi, sir.

183
00:14:49,167 --> 00:14:51,733
- Where do we go?
- Right here, sir.

184
00:14:51,867 --> 00:14:53,067
Ma'am. Just here.

185
00:14:53,200 --> 00:14:56,767
How was your speech therapy
earlier?

186
00:14:56,900 --> 00:14:58,667
It went well.

187
00:14:58,800 --> 00:15:01,567
Thank God.

188
00:15:01,733 --> 00:15:03,833
That's good to hear, Ma'am.

189
00:15:03,967 --> 00:15:06,233
You just need to be patient.

190
00:15:06,367 --> 00:15:12,300
For our PT sessions, we'll start
with simple exercises.

191
00:15:12,433 --> 00:15:13,433
Sitting up,

192
00:15:13,567 --> 00:15:15,200
standing,

193
00:15:15,333 --> 00:15:17,333
and eventually walking again.

194
00:15:17,467 --> 00:15:21,867
This will help
your body and brain

195
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:23,833
learn to work together again.

196
00:15:23,967 --> 00:15:25,600
So, Ma'am, are you ready?

197
00:15:26,667 --> 00:15:29,167
Let's begin.

198
00:15:29,300 --> 00:15:36,167
I'll get better for my children
and my loved ones.

199
00:15:37,767 --> 00:15:42,333
Ma'am, let's start
with deep breathing.

200
00:15:42,467 --> 00:15:44,267
Inhale andn exhale.

201
00:15:44,400 --> 00:15:49,133
Inhale slowly,
then exhale through your mouth.

202
00:15:49,267 --> 00:15:50,933
Slowly.

203
00:15:51,067 --> 00:15:51,833
Exhale.

204
00:15:51,967 --> 00:15:53,167
Good.

205
00:15:53,300 --> 00:15:54,333
One more.

206
00:15:54,467 --> 00:15:55,867
Last one, Ma'am.

207
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:57,267
Inhale.

208
00:15:57,400 --> 00:15:58,767
Let's begin, Ma'am.

209
00:16:58,133 --> 00:17:00,367
Noah?

210
00:17:03,267 --> 00:17:04,600
Sorry.

211
00:17:07,400 --> 00:17:13,100
We didn't get married

212
00:17:13,233 --> 00:17:20,033
because I broke up with you.

213
00:17:28,233 --> 00:17:30,167
You just led me on.

214
00:17:30,300 --> 00:17:32,500
Wasn't she awful to me, kids?

215
00:17:37,267 --> 00:17:43,267
Why did I do that to you?

216
00:17:43,400 --> 00:17:48,400
You were the perfect man
to marry.

217
00:17:53,133 --> 00:17:56,433
Mom, to be honest...

218
00:17:56,833 --> 00:17:59,067
you and Dad really fixed things.

219
00:18:01,033 --> 00:18:02,167
And, Mom,

220
00:18:03,200 --> 00:18:06,967
you and Dad got back together.
You already forgave each other.

221
00:18:08,800 --> 00:18:10,267
Is that true?

222
00:18:15,067 --> 00:18:22,100
Why don't I remember any of it?

223
00:18:23,433 --> 00:18:25,333
To be honest, Mom...

224
00:18:26,567 --> 00:18:29,167
We're almost a complete family
again.

225
00:18:30,333 --> 00:18:32,933
The only thing missing is you
and Dad getting married.

226
00:18:56,900 --> 00:18:57,933
Felma?

227
00:19:01,267 --> 00:19:04,800
<i>I ruined your life and the lives
of our children.</i>

228
00:19:04,933 --> 00:19:07,967
<i>The pain is still here,
but that part is over.</i>

229
00:19:08,100 --> 00:19:10,767
<i>It's not right for me
to stay tied to anger.</i>

230
00:19:10,900 --> 00:19:12,400
<i> I forgive you.</i>

231
00:19:28,300 --> 00:19:29,900
Manuel?

232
00:19:39,600 --> 00:19:40,433
Felma.

233
00:19:41,733 --> 00:19:42,733
My love.

234
00:19:45,300 --> 00:19:46,800
I'm sorry.

235
00:19:49,767 --> 00:19:59,733
I didn't remember right away
that we already made up.

236
00:20:05,633 --> 00:20:06,567
But...

237
00:20:07,600 --> 00:20:10,867
honestly...

238
00:20:13,267 --> 00:20:15,933
At this moment,

239
00:20:17,700 --> 00:20:27,667
my memory still isn't fully
back.

240
00:20:32,367 --> 00:20:33,733
That's okay, Felma.

241
00:20:34,900 --> 00:20:36,600
I understand.

242
00:20:39,633 --> 00:20:44,133
No matter how long it takes
for your memories to return,

243
00:20:45,467 --> 00:20:47,500
I'm willing to wait.

244
00:20:49,067 --> 00:20:59,033
But my heart feels
that I love you.

245
00:21:11,200 --> 00:21:21,167
And the kids and I need you.

246
00:21:22,167 --> 00:21:24,433
I love you so much, too, Felma.

247
00:21:26,533 --> 00:21:27,967
So very much.

248
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:21,233
How's your new job?

249
00:22:21,367 --> 00:22:23,167
Are you doing your best?

250
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:42,100
When they found out that Jessica
wasn't really their sister,

251
00:22:42,233 --> 00:22:43,300
they hurt her...

252
00:22:43,433 --> 00:22:44,633
abused her...

253
00:22:44,767 --> 00:22:46,400
until our child died.

254
00:22:46,533 --> 00:22:50,233
The annulment has to succeed,
then we'll get married, right?

255
00:22:50,400 --> 00:22:55,267
You'll still marry me?

256
00:22:55,400 --> 00:22:59,967
I'll make them answer for
everything they did to you

257
00:23:00,100 --> 00:23:01,333
and Jessica.

258
00:23:01,467 --> 00:23:04,033
She was such a good child.
So caring.

259
00:23:04,167 --> 00:23:06,000
I loved my youngest so much.

260
00:23:06,133 --> 00:23:07,900
Manuel was close to Jessica.

261
00:23:08,033 --> 00:23:11,600
From his stories,
he truly loved our child.
